'''''Supernova''''' is a [[studio album]] by The Gonzalo Rubalcaba Trio released by [[Blue Note Records]] on July 17, 2001.  The trio consisted of [[Gonzalo Rubalcaba]] on piano, bassist Carlos Henriguez, and drummer [[Ignacio Berroa]]. It peaked at number 25 in the ''Billboard'' [[Top Jazz Albums]] chart.

[[record producer|Produced]] by Rubalcaba, the album was released following his collaborative work with [[Charlie Haden]] on the album ''[[Nocturne (Charlie Haden album)|Nocturne]]'', which resulted in a [[Grammy Award]] for Haden. ''Supernova'' includes nine tracks and met with mostly positive reviews by critics, most commenting on the versatility and musical ability of the performer. The album was further nominated for a Grammy, a [[Billboard Latin Music Awards|''Billboard'' Latin Music Award]], and earned the [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Latin Jazz Album|Latin Grammy for Best Latin Jazz Album]].

==Background and release==
Cuban pianist [[Gonzalo Rubalcaba]] recorded ''Supernova'' following his collaboration with [[Charlie Haden]] on the album ''[[Nocturne (Charlie Haden album)|Nocturne]]'', which was co-produced, performed and orchestrated by Rubalcaba.<ref name=round2/> The pianist was named the "most visible musical presence" in ''Nocturne'' and the album received the [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Jazz Album]] at the [[2002 Grammy Awards|44th Grammy Awards]], after being referred to as an "engaging blend of jazz and Latin song" by Don Heckman of ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.<ref name=catalina/><ref name=experience>{{cite news |first=Don |last=Heckman |title=Experience Pays Off Again|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/feb/28/entertainment/et-jazz28|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=April 9, 2013|date=February 28, 2002}}</ref> About ''Supernova'', Rubalcaba stated that blends the melodic tone of his previous album (''Inner Voyage'') and the lyricism of his early records.<ref name="leila">
{{cite journal|last=Cobo|first=Leila|date=February 23, 2002|title=Latin Notas|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Company|Nielsen Business Media, Inc.]]|volume=114|issue=8|page=32|url=http://books.google.com.mx/books?id=JBAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA32&dq=gonzalo+rubalcaba+supernova&hl=es-419&sa=X&ei=sm9oUYOoFemciALnu4GoAQ&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=gonzalo%20rubalcaba%20supernova&f=false|accessdate=April 12, 2013}}</ref> 

On May 2001, three months before the album release, Rubalcaba along with bassist Carlos Henriguez and drummer [[Ignacio Berroa]] (The Gonzalo Rubalcaba Trio), debuted some of the tracks at the Catalina Jazz Club in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], without telling his audience beforehand.<ref name=catalina>{{cite news |first=Don |last=Heckman |title=Rubalcaba Trio's Explosive New Rhythms|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/may/04/entertainment/ca-59073|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=April 9, 2013|date=May 4, 2001}}</ref> Heckman described the songs as "pieces roved through unusual metric territory, with explosive accents bursting out of the rhythmic flow."<ref name=catalina/> The album was released by [[Blue Note Records]] on July 17, 2001, becoming Rubalcaba's seventh album for the label.<ref name="all">{{cite web|title=Supernova&nbsp;<U+2014> Gonzalo Rubalcaba|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=supernova-mw0000006394|pure_url=yes}} |accessdate=April 12, 2013 |first=Bret|last=Love|work=''[[Allmusic]]'' |publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]}}</ref><ref name=j-review>{{cite news |first=Don |last=Williamson |title=Supernova by Gonzalo Rubalbaca|url=http://www.jazzreview.com/index.php/reviews/latest-cd-reviews/item/18191-|publisher=[[Jazz Review]] |work=[[Jazz Review]]|accessdate=April 13, 2013|date=May 18, 2001}}</ref>

==Content==
The album includes nine tracks, five original songs and four covers.<ref name=pop-matters>{{cite news |first=Matt|last=Cibula|title=Gonzalo Rubalcaba: Supernova|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/rubalcabagonzalo-supernova/|publisher=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=April 12, 2013|date=July 16, 2001}}</ref> The title track is separated in two takes, "Supernova 1" and "Supernova 2".<ref name=about>{{cite news |first=Mark|last=Corroto|title=Gonzalo Rubalcaba: Supernova (2002)|url=http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/article.php?id=8425#.UWjXuqJJOAg|work=[[All About Jazz]]|publisher=[[All About Jazz]]|accessdate=April 12, 2013|date=August 1, 2001}}</ref> The first one shifts constantly the time signature becoming a "stop-and-start" [[mambo (music)|mambo]].<ref name="all"/><ref name=pop-matters/> Matt Cibula of ''[[PopMatters]]'' highlights the work of Berroa on the [[drum kit|drums]] and Henriquez' [[bass guitar|bass]], giving both pieces a "solid foundation".<ref name=pop-matters/> The second track, "El Cadete Constitucional", was written by Jacobo Rubalcaba (the pianist grandfather), as a children's song and adapted into a funky strut in its step,<ref name="all"/> opening as a "throwback to early Cuban jazz", and ending with a very "modern" synthesizer solo.<ref name=about/> The song features additional [[percussion]] by Robert and Luis Quintero.<ref name=pop-matters/> "[[The Peanut Vendor|El Manicero]]", an American standard since 1930, also has and additional participation by the Quintero brothers.<ref name=pop-matters/> "Alma Mia" is a ballad,<ref name="all"/> considered a Mexican standard on which the trio applies "honest melancholy lyricism."<ref name=about/> "The Hard One" is a re-recording of the original take included on Rubalcaba's ''Inner Voyage'' (1999). The track samples "[[Take Five]]" by [[Dave Brubeck]], and features Rubalcaba's piano rumbling in "metrical unpredictability."<ref name=j-review/><ref name=pop-matters/><ref name=about/> "La Voz del Centro" is a [[Waltz (music)#Jazz waltzes|waltz]].<ref name=pop-matters/> The last song, "Oren", it is an "enviromental piece" with drums and piano, deemed as "pretty but trivial".<ref name=pop-matters/><ref name=about/>

==Reception and accolades==
{{Album ratings
| rev1 = [[All About Jazz]]<ref name=about/>
| rev1Score = (positive)
| rev2 = [[Allmusic]]<ref name="all"/>
| rev2Score = ''{{rating|4.5|5}}''
| rev3 = ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''<ref name=bill-review/>
| rev3Score = (positive)
| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''<ref name=ew/>
| rev4Score = (B+)
| rev5 = ''[[Jazz Review]]''<ref name=j-review/>
| rev5Score = ''{{rating|5|5}}''
| rev6 = ''[[Metro Times]]''<ref name=metro/>
| rev6Score = (positive)
| rev7 = ''[[PopMatters]]''<ref name=pop-matters/>
| rev7Score = (mixed)
}}
''Supernova'' received positive reviews from critics. Bret Love of [[Allmusic]] gave the album 4.5 stars out of five, calling it "a wonderful album of varying moods and textures."<ref name="all"/> Leila Cobo of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' magazine named the album an "acomplished work that highlights a more introspective and versatile Rubalcaba."<ref name="leila"/> On the album review, Cobo also commented that "this [''Supernova''] is a refreshing outing."<ref name=bill-review>{{cite news |title=Supernova|first=Leila|last=Cobo|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/75808/2002-billboard-latin-music-awards|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=April 11, 2013|year=2001}}</ref> [[All About Jazz]]' Mark Corroto stated that the album proves that the performer "has plenty of heart rooted in a traditional Cuban music past and a head pointed into a diverse North American future."<ref name=about/> Matt Cibula of ''[[PopMatters]]'' stated that ''Supernova'' is a "wonderful record, that proves that Rubalcaba is one of the greatest composers and pianist in the world," but was critical about the lack of emotional commitment to his music, concluding that the album would work better on an audience that never heard the performer before.<ref name=pop-matters/> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the album a B+ grade, arguing that the album "neatly showcases Rubalcaba's strengths: unerring yet playful rhythm, technical ferocity when required, burnished balladry, and Cuban swagger blended with jazz suavity."<ref name=ew>{{cite news |first=Josef |last=Woodard |title=Gonzalo Rubalcaba: Supernova (2013)|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,255748,00.html|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time, Inc]]|accessdate=April 13, 2013|date=July 20, 2001}}</ref> George Tysh of ''[[Metro Times]]'' stated that ''Supernova'' "incorporates both Rubalcaba personalities, being more percussively rhythmic (definitely more Latin) than ''Inner Voyage'', but still as sensitive."<ref name=metro>{{cite news |first=George|last=Tysh|title=Piano mas|url=http://www2.metrotimes.com/archives/review.asp?rid=12100|work=[[Metro Times]]|publisher=[[Detroit Metro Times]]|accessdate=April 13, 2013|date=August 8, 2001}}</ref> ''[[Jazz Review]]'' granted the album a perfect score of five stars, with Don Williamson stating that the album "continues to prove that Rubalcaba is dedicated to the authenticity, the tradition and the spirit of the Cuban music he studied and which is part of his being."<ref name=j-review/> The Rubalcaba's biography included on the book ''Jazz for Dummies'' (2006) by Dick Sutro, emphasizes that the album founds the performer on his peak form.<ref name=sutro>{{Cite book|last=Sutro|first=Dirk|title=Jazz for Dummies|year=2006|publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons|Wiley Publishing, Inc]]|isbn=978-0-471-76844-9|ref=harv|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>

Rubalcaba received a nomination for a Grammy Award for Best Latin Jazz Album in [[2002 Grammy Awards|2002]] for ''Supernova'', which was awarded to Haden's ''Nocturne''.<ref name=round2>{{cite news |first=Oscar |last=Garza |title=It's Haden Versus Rubalcaba, Round 2, at Latin Grammys|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/jul/27/entertainment/et-bright27|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=April 9, 2013|date=July 27, 2002}}</ref> Both albums were nominated the following year to the [[Latin Grammy Awards of 2002|Latin Grammy Award]] in the [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Latin Jazz Album|same field]].<ref name=round2/> According to musician [[David S<U+00E1>nchez (musician)|David S<U+00E1>nchez]], the award was Rubalcaba's to lose since Haden was not [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]].<ref name=round2/> ''Supernova'' earned the Latin Grammy.<ref name=winners>{{cite news |title=The List of Winners|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/sep/19/news/mn-grammylist19|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=April 9, 2013|date=September 19, 2002}}</ref> The track "Oren" was nominated for a [[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Composition]], which it lost to [[Alan Silvestri]]'s "Cast Away (End Credits)".<ref name="oren-grammy">
{{cite journal|date=January 19, 2002|title=Final Nominations for the 44th Annual Grammy Awards|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Company|Nielsen Business Media, Inc.]]|volume=114|issue=3|page=91|url=http://books.google.com.mx/books?id=1Q8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA91&dq=supernova+gonzalo+rubalcaba&hl=es-419&sa=X&ei=6cVpUdSzDuTQiwLA_4CADg&ved=0CDIQ6AEwADge#v=onepage&q=supernova%20gonzalo%20rubalcaba&f=false|accessdate=April 12, 2013}}</ref> ''Supernova'' reached number two at the ''[[CMJ]]'' Jazz Albums chart and peaked at number 25 in the ''Billboard'' [[Top Jazz Albums]] chart and was nominated for "Latin Jazz Album of the Year" at the [[2002 Latin Billboard Music Awards|13th Annual ''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]], losing to ''Latin Spirits'' by [[Poncho Sanchez]].<ref name="all"/><ref name="cmj">{{cite journal|date=October 16, 2001|title=Jazz|journal=[[CMJ]]|publisher=The CMJ Network, Inc. |volume=69|issue=737|page=27|url=http://books.google.com.mx/books?id=CFMxac4MxfYC&pg=PT26&dq=supernova+gonzalo+rubalcaba&hl=es-419&sa=X&ei=681pUb-3KKmBiwK16YDICw&ved=0CEUQ6AEwBA|accessdate=April 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=bill-2002>{{cite news |title=2002 Billboard Latin Music Awards|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/75808/2002-billboard-latin-music-awards|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=April 11, 2013|year=2002}}</ref>

